I am writing to request the opportunity to inspect and copy public records in your control and custody, pursuant to Public Records Act, La.R.S. 44:1, et seq. I request all information held by the New Orleans Police Department regarding the following case: 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NOPD Item&nbsp;H-11027-10 
 This item number corresponds to a non-fatal shooting in which the victim was identified as&nbsp;Shaquille Cooper aka "Shaq." 
 This request includes, but is not limited to, any and all incident and supplemental records, documents, reports, analyses, notes, memoranda, audio tapes, charts and any other records not exempted from the Louisiana Public Records Act. I request these records whether they be in an individual officers’ files, in the possession of members or former members of the New Orleans Police Department, on microfilm or microfiche, or otherwise stored or maintained. 
 Louisiana’s Public Record Act, La R.S. 44:3 states that records of law enforcement agencies can be exempted “pending criminal litigation or any criminal litigation which can be reasonably anticipated....” That standard does not apply in this situation. Regarding the records of law enforcement agencies, the Louisiana Supreme Court has ruled that “the Public Records Act must be liberally construed in favor of public access,” and that access “can be denied only when the law specifically and unequivocally provides against access.” Harrison v. Norris, 569 So. 2d 585 (La 1990). See also Lemmon v. Connick, 590 So. 2d 574, (La 1991).&nbsp; 
 I request that you direct each division or department of the NOPD that may have evidence of any kind relating to these requests to make those items available to me also, within the time provided for by the Public Records Act. I request access to the above-mentioned records, so that I, or my designees, may review and copy them. Any copying costs will be paid upon submission of an invoice for reasonable fees.&nbsp;&nbsp; 
 Should you determine any of the requested materials to be exempt from public disclosure, I would also request, in writing, a list of each document being withheld, along with a basis under the law for your contention that each record is exempt from the Public Records Act. See La. R.S. 44:32(D). Please notify me regarding your response within three days, as required by law. I appreciate your attention to this matter. 
 &nbsp; 
 Sincerely, 
 Ryan Jawetz

