Date:&nbsp; October 2, 2017 
 &nbsp; 
 To:&nbsp; New Orleans Police Department 
 &nbsp; 
 Subject:&nbsp; Reuters News Public Records Request, Via&nbsp;Records Form 
 &nbsp; 
 I am a journalist for Reuters News. I hereby request the following data, records and information pursuant to the Louisiana Public Records Law.&nbsp; I am hoping to receive these records by Oct. 23, 2017.&nbsp; Please keep me up-to-date on the progress, and let me know if there is a way to narrow my request to make it quicker and easier for you to fill.&nbsp; 
 &nbsp; 
 In a PowerPoint slide provided by Taser International (which recently changed its name to Axon Enterprise), the company stated the following about statistics from the New Orleans Police Department: 
 &nbsp; 
 Statistics from NOPD PIB: Use of Force Incident Reports 
 2008 injured officers 64 
 2009 injured officers 26 &nbsp;(59% ▼) 
 2010 injured officers 6 (77% ▼) 
 &nbsp; 
 Priority 1 
 This is the priority part of my request: 
 &nbsp; 

 The year the New Orleans Police Department began using Tasers. 
 For the New Orleans Police Department:&nbsp; The total number of officers injured, from Use of Force Incident Reports, on an annual basis for 1999 – 2016. 

 &nbsp; 
 Priority 2 
 I am also requesting the following data, but depending on availability and how long it would take to pull.&nbsp; If the items listed under “Priority 2” would hold up filling the request for the items in “Priority 1” please call me and let me know, because I might want to adjust my request. 
 &nbsp; 

 For the New Orleans Police Department:&nbsp; The total dollar value of workers’ compensation claims, resulting from Use of Force incidents, for officers on an annual basis for 1999 - 2016. 
 For the New Orleans Police Department:&nbsp; The total number of suspects injured, from Use of Force incidents, on an annual basis for 1999 - 2016. 

 &nbsp; 
 Date Range 
 I am asking for the data on an annual basis for 1999 – 2016.&nbsp; I realize this is a long range.&nbsp; For each portion of the request, if data is not available going back as far as 1999, please let me know and we can discuss what is available and I can change my request to reflect that timeframe. &nbsp;Or, if the data is available back to 1999 but going back that far would add a significant amount of time and effort, please let me know and we can also discuss. 
 &nbsp; 
 Format 
 I prefer to receive records in the following formats, listed in order of preference: (1) an electronic data format such as a spreadsheet, delimited data set, database file, or similar structured data file; (2) other non-proprietary electronic format.&nbsp; I am hoping that these records are already kept on an annual basis, perhaps in some kind of database or annual report.&nbsp; If these records are not readily available in an electronic data format, but are available in some form of report that already exists (such as an annual report to the city council), please send me the reports. 
 &nbsp; 
 If you decide to exempt a portion of any record, please release all other segregable parts. If you withhold any record or portion of a record, please specify which statutory exemptions are claimed for each withholding. 
 &nbsp; 
 Fee Waiver Request 
 If there are any search, review, or duplication fees greater than $25, please inform me before you fill the request. But first please consider my requests for fee reduction and fee waiver. This request is being made in connection with Reuters News’ newsgathering functions and not for any other commercial purpose. Reuters News intends to produce one or more original investigative reports based on analysis of the requested information that will inform the public about how tax dollars are used in New Orleans. 
 &nbsp; 
 If you have any questions about any aspect of this request, please contact me at paula.seligson@thomsonreuters.com or 919-744-9190. 
 &nbsp; 
 Thank you for your attention to this request. 
 &nbsp; 
 Paula Seligson 
 National Affairs  
 919-744-9190 
 paula.seligson@tr.com 
 Reuters News

I am working on a journalism project at Stanford University. We are collecting data on pedestrian and traffic stops and searches made by cities across the country. 
 &nbsp;I am requesting the raw data of traffic stops and pedestrian stops made by the New Orleans&nbsp;Police Department&nbsp;and laid out in your record description for the last ten (10) years. The fields of data we are requesting include, but are not limited to:&nbsp; 

 case number and&nbsp;complaint 
 defendant gender, race, and DOB 
 vehicle year, color, make, model, style, and state in which it is registered 
 date of incident, time of incident, location of incident and milepost 
 approximate speed and posted speed&nbsp; 
 any violations and/or sanctions, whether a search was conducted, whether contraband was found, whether the person was arrested and what type of enforcement took place.&nbsp; 
 officer ID number,&nbsp;race,&nbsp;gender 
 officer date of birth and information on years of service&nbsp; 

 To be clear, this request is for all data from traffic stops and pedestrian stops considered to be public record. This includes, but is not limited to, the above list of data types.&nbsp; 
 This request is not being made for commercial purposes. We ask that the request be provided electronically. We can accept the data in many common formats, including as CSV, tab-separated file, spreadsheet or other database formats. Data can be emailed to&nbsp;a Box folder at NEW_ORL.8c2kuel4z4jv5vu2@u.box.com. 
 In the event data must be sent physically on a CD or portable drive, please mail to:&nbsp; 
